      \field{labelnamesource}{author}
      \field{labeltitlesource}{title}
      \field{abstract}{In sugarcane production, irrigation scheduling based on accurate estimation of the water status is essential to ensure profitable yields. Water stress causes an increment in leaf surface temperature since stomatal closure reduces transpiration; therefore, canopy temperature (CT) is recognized as a useful tool for water stress detection. Thermography could be an alternative way, yet few reports are available on its use in sugarcane. In the present study, we established well-watered and water-stressed sugarcane canopies and acquired CT readings and thermal images, concurrently measuring photosynthesis under a greenhouse condition to validate the usability of thermography. Water suspension raised the soil pF up to the permanent wilting point, putting the water-stressed canopy under a highly dry condition. The shortage of water hardly altered the appearance of sugarcane but significantly dropped photosynthesis and transpiration rates, resulting in increasing CT. The colorings of thermal images were also greatly affected by the water stress; consequently, it became easier to distinguish the well-watered and water-stressed canopies. R gray level was most sensitive to the changes in CT among colors, suggesting that it could be a good indicator of sugarcane water status. Since crop water stress index calculated from transpiration rate was well correlated with the differences of CT and R gray level between the canopies, our study demonstrated that both CT measurement and thermography are useful for water stress detection, however, considering its ease of evaluation and small differences of CT in case of bad weather, the use of thermal images could be more recommended.}
